# EasyMultiOmics: Short-read metagenomic analysis workflow

```bash
# Version: 1.01, 2026/04/30
# Tested on CentOS 7 / Linux
# Module: Short-read metagenomics
# Description:
# This workflow performs quality control, taxonomic profiling, ARG annotation,
# metagenomic assembly, genome binning, MAG quality assessment, MAG taxonomy,
# SGB clustering and phylogenetic tree construction.
```

---

# 0. Basic configuration

## 0.1 Set sample name and computational resources

```bash
# Use the first command-line argument as the sample name
sample=$1

# Set the number of CPU threads
threads=24

# Define paired-end short-read input files
R1=${sample}_R1.fastq.gz
R2=${sample}_R2.fastq.gz

# Stop the script immediately if any command fails
set -euo pipefail
```

**Explanation:**  
This section defines the basic input information. The variable `sample` is provided when running the script. For example:

```bash
bash EasyMultiOmics_short_read.sh sample01
```

The script will automatically recognize the following input files:

```bash
sample01_R1.fastq.gz
sample01_R2.fastq.gz
```

`threads=24` means that 24 CPU threads will be used for tools that support parallel computing.

---

## 0.2 Set database paths

```bash
# Kraken2 / Bracken database
KRAKEN2_DB=/path/to/kraken2_database

# ARGs_OAP database and classification structure file
ARG_DB=/path/to/database.fasta
ARG_STRUCTURE=/path/to/structure.txt

# GTDB-Tk database
GTDBTK_DB=/path/to/gtdbtk_database

# PhyloPhlAn database and configuration file
PHYLOPHLAN_DB=phylophlan_databases/phylophlan
PHYLOPHLAN_CFG=/ifs1/Software/Miniconda3/envs/phylophlan/lib/python3.13/site-packages/phylophlan/phylophlan_configs/supermatrix_aa.cfg
```

**Explanation:**  
This section defines the database paths required by different tools. Before running the workflow, all `/path/to/...` paths should be replaced with the real paths on your server.

Required databases include:

- Kraken2 / Bracken database for taxonomic profiling
- ARGs_OAP database for antibiotic resistance gene annotation
- GTDB-Tk database for MAG taxonomic classification
- PhyloPhlAn database for phylogenetic tree construction

---

## 0.3 Create output directories

```bash
mkdir -p QC
mkdir -p Taxonomy
mkdir -p ARGs
mkdir -p Assembly
mkdir -p Binning
mkdir -p Bin_QC
mkdir -p Bin_Taxonomy
mkdir -p SGBs
mkdir -p SGBs/MAGs
mkdir -p SGBs/repre_MAGs
mkdir -p SGBs/scripts
```

**Explanation:**  
This section creates all output directories used in the workflow. The results of different analysis modules will be stored in separate folders to keep the project organized.

---

# 1. Raw data quality control

## 1.1 Quality filtering and adapter trimming using fastp

```bash
# Activate the conda environment containing fastp
conda activate fastp

# Perform quality control for paired-end short reads
fastp \
  -i ${R1} \
  -I ${R2} \
  -o QC/${sample}_clean_R1.fastq.gz \
  -O QC/${sample}_clean_R2.fastq.gz \
  -h QC/${sample}_fastp.html \
  -j QC/${sample}_fastp.json \
  -w ${threads}
```

**Explanation:**  
This step uses `fastp` to perform quality control of paired-end short-read metagenomic sequencing data.

Main functions include:

- adapter trimming
- low-quality base removal
- low-quality read filtering
- quality report generation

Main output files:

```bash
QC/${sample}_clean_R1.fastq.gz
QC/${sample}_clean_R2.fastq.gz
QC/${sample}_fastp.html
QC/${sample}_fastp.json
```

The cleaned reads will be used for all downstream analyses.

---

# 2. Read-based taxonomic profiling

## 2.1 Taxonomic classification using Kraken2

```bash
# Activate the conda environment containing Kraken2
conda activate kraken2

# Perform read-based taxonomic classification
kraken2 \
  --db ${KRAKEN2_DB} \
  --threads ${threads} \
  --paired \
  --gzip-compressed \
  --report Taxonomy/${sample}_kraken2_report.txt \
  --output Taxonomy/${sample}_kraken2_output.txt \
  QC/${sample}_clean_R1.fastq.gz \
  QC/${sample}_clean_R2.fastq.gz
```

**Explanation:**  
Kraken2 classifies metagenomic reads based on k-mer matching against a reference database.

Main output files:

```bash
Taxonomy/${sample}_kraken2_report.txt
Taxonomy/${sample}_kraken2_output.txt
```

The `kraken2_report.txt` file is used as the input for Bracken abundance estimation.

---

## 2.2 Species-level abundance estimation using Bracken

```bash
# Activate the conda environment containing Bracken
conda activate bracken

# Estimate species-level abundance based on Kraken2 results
bracken \
  -d ${KRAKEN2_DB} \
  -i Taxonomy/${sample}_kraken2_report.txt \
  -o Taxonomy/${sample}_bracken_species.txt \
  -r 150 \
  -l S \
  -t 10
```

**Explanation:**  
Bracken estimates species-level abundance based on Kraken2 classification results.

Important parameters:

```bash
-r 150
```

This means the read length is set to 150 bp. Modify this value according to your actual sequencing read length.

```bash
-l S
```

This means abundance will be estimated at the species level.

```bash
-t 10
```

This is the minimum read threshold, not the number of threads.

Main output file:

```bash
Taxonomy/${sample}_bracken_species.txt
```

---

# 3. ARG annotation and quantification using ARGs_OAP

## 3.1 Prepare input files for ARGs_OAP

```bash
# Activate the conda environment containing ARGs_OAP and seqkit
conda activate args_oap

# Create output directories for ARGs_OAP
mkdir -p ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP
mkdir -p ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_one
mkdir -p ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_two

# Convert cleaned FASTQ files to FASTA format
seqkit fq2fa QC/${sample}_clean_R1.fastq.gz > ARGs/${sample}_R1.clean.fa
seqkit fq2fa QC/${sample}_clean_R2.fastq.gz > ARGs/${sample}_R2.clean.fa

# Merge paired-end reads into one FASTA file
cat ARGs/${sample}_R1.clean.fa \
    ARGs/${sample}_R2.clean.fa \
    > ARGs/${sample}_clean_reads.fa
```

**Explanation:**  
ARGs_OAP can use FASTA-format input in this workflow. Therefore, the cleaned FASTQ files are first converted into FASTA files using `seqkit fq2fa`.

Main output file:

```bash
ARGs/${sample}_clean_reads.fa
```

This merged FASTA file will be used for ARG annotation.

---

## 3.2 Optional: build customized ARGs_OAP database

```bash
# Use this step only when a customized ARG database is required
# The database may contain nucleotide or amino acid sequences

# args_oap make_db \
#   -i /path/to/custom_database.fasta
```

**Explanation:**  
This step is optional. If you want to use a customized antibiotic resistance gene database, you can build it using `args_oap make_db`.

If you are using the default or already prepared ARGs_OAP database, this step can be skipped.

---

## 3.3 Stage one: ARG annotation

```bash
# Perform ARG annotation using ARGs_OAP
args_oap stage_one \
  -i ARGs/${sample}_clean_reads.fa \
  -o ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_one \
  -f fa \
  -t ${threads} \
  --database ${ARG_DB}
```

**Explanation:**  
This step performs ARG annotation by comparing metagenomic reads against the ARG database.

Main output directory:

```bash
ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_one
```

This directory contains the preliminary ARG annotation results.

---

## 3.4 Stage two: ARG classification and quantification

```bash
# Classify and quantify annotated ARGs
args_oap stage_two \
  -i ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_one \
  -o ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_two \
  -t ${threads} \
  --database ${ARG_DB} \
  --structure1 ${ARG_STRUCTURE}
```

**Explanation:**  
This step classifies and quantifies ARGs based on the annotation results from stage one.

Main output directory:

```bash
ARGs/${sample}_ARGs_OAP/stage_two
```

This step usually generates ARG abundance tables and classification results.

Note: different ARGs_OAP versions may use slightly different parameters. Before formal analysis, check the command-line help:

```bash
args_oap -h
args_oap stage_one -h
args_oap stage_two -h
```

